{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.13","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[],"dockerImageVersionId":31400,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Probability Spaces - The Triple (Ω, F, P)\n\n> **Durrett Ch. 1.1 — Probability Spaces**\n\n---\n\n## What is it?\n\nA **probability space** is a mathematical triple **(Ω, F, P)**:\n\n| Symbol | Name | Meaning |\n|--------|------|---------|\n| **Ω** | Sample space | The set of all possible outcomes |\n| **F** | σ-field (σ-algebra) | The collection of measurable events |\n| **P** | Probability measure | A function assigning probability to each event |\n\n\n### The σ-field F\n\nF is a collection of subsets of Ω satisfying:\n1. **Closure under complement**: if A ∈ F, then Aᶜ ∈ F\n2. **Closure under countable union**: if A₁, A₂, ... ∈ F, then ∪ᵢAᵢ ∈ F\n\nThis ensures we can talk about \"the complement of an event\" and \"one of these events happening\" — both are still valid events.\n\n\n### The Probability Measure P\n\nP: F → [0, 1] satisfying:\n1. **Non-negativity**: P(A) ≥ P(∅) = 0\n2. **Normalization**: P(Ω) = 1\n3. **Countable additivity** (σ-additivity): for disjoint events A₁, A₂, ...,\n   P(∪ᵢAᵢ) = Σᵢ P(Aᵢ)\n\n---\n\n## Why Does This Matter?\n\nWithout this rigorous foundation, probability collapses on edge cases:\n- **Infinite sample spaces** (e.g., continuous distributions) need σ-fields to avoid paradoxes (Vitali sets — unmeasurable sets exist!)\n- **LLMs generate from continuous distributions** — the theoretical backbone is measure theory\n- **RLHF reward models** output real-valued scores; their statistical properties require measure-theoretic probability\n\nThe Kolmogorov axioms above give us a *consistent* framework that works for both discrete (token IDs) and continuous (logits, embeddings) probability.\n\n---\n\n## Key Consequences\n\n### Monotonicity\nIf A ⊂ B, then P(A) ≤ P(B)\n\n### Union bound (Borel-Cantelli flavor)\nP(A ∪ B) ≤ P(A) + P(B)  ← used constantly in ML theory proofs\n\n### Continuity\n- From below: if Aₙ ↑ A, then P(Aₙ) ↑ P(A)\n- From above: if Aₙ ↓ A (with P(A₁) < ∞), then P(Aₙ) ↓ P(A)\n\n---\n\n## Concrete Examples\n\n### Example 1: Coin flip (discrete)\n- Ω = {H, T}\n- F = {∅, {H}, {T}, {H,T}}\n- P({H}) = 0.5, P({T}) = 0.5\n\n### Example 2: Language model token (discrete but large)\n- Ω = {token₀, token₁, ..., token₅₀₂₅₅}  (vocabulary)\n- F = all subsets of Ω (powerset)\n- P = softmax output distribution\n\n### Example 3: Real-valued output (continuous)\n- Ω = ℝ (e.g., an embedding dimension value)\n- F = Borel sets B(ℝ) — the σ-field generated by all open intervals\n- P = Gaussian measure N(0, 1)\n\n---\n\n## Borel Sets — Why They Matter for LLMs\n\nThe **Borel σ-field** B(ℝ) is the smallest σ-field containing all open intervals.\n\nWhen you compute P(logit > threshold) in a language model, you're computing the probability measure of a Borel set — this is only well-defined because we have a proper σ-field.\n\n---\n\n## Connection to Modern LLM Techniques\n\n| Probability Concept | LLM Application |\n|--------------------|-----------------|\n| Sample space Ω | Vocabulary (token IDs) or ℝⁿ (embedding space) |\n| Events in F | \"next token is in set S\", \"embedding is in region R\" |\n| P (probability measure) | Softmax distribution over vocabulary |\n| Conditional measure P(·\\|context) | Autoregressive language modeling |\n| Product space Ω^T | Sequence of T tokens — joint distribution |\n| σ-additivity | Probability sums across all tokens = 1 |\n\n**DPO/RLHF connection**: The reward model R(x, y) implicitly defines a probability measure P(y is preferred | x) over the space of completions. The DPO objective is derived by treating the optimal policy as a Gibbs/Boltzmann distribution — which requires a proper probability space.\n\n---\n\n## Key Intuition\n\nThink of the triple as:\n- **Ω**: the universe of \"what can happen\"\n- **F**: the \"questions we're allowed to ask\" about Ω\n- **P**: the \"answers\" (how likely each question's answer is \"yes\")\n\nNot every subset of Ω needs to be measurable (in F) — only those subsets we care about and that don't lead to paradoxes.\n\n---\n\n## Reference\n- Durrett §1.1 (Probability Spaces)\n- Durrett Appendix A.1 (Carathéodory's Extension Theorem)","metadata":{"_uuid":"8f2839f25d086af736a60e9eeb907d3b93b6e0e5","_cell_guid":"b1076dfc-b9ad-4769-8c92-a6c4dae69d19"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Concepts: (Omega, F, P) triple, sigma-fields, probability axioms,\n#           union bound, continuity of measure, Borel sets.\n# Connection: LLM softmax distributions as probability measures.\n\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom fractions import Fraction\n\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 1. Discrete Probability Space: Coin Flip\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\nclass DiscreteProbabilitySpace:\n    \"\"\"\n    A finite probability space (Omega, F, P).\n    F = power set of Omega (all subsets are measurable).\n    \"\"\"\n\n    def __init__(self, outcomes: list, probabilities: list):\n        assert abs(sum(probabilities) - 1.0) < 1e-9, \"Probabilities must sum to 1\"\n        assert all(p >= 0 for p in probabilities), \"Probabilities must be non-negative\"\n        self.omega = outcomes\n        self.p_map = dict(zip(outcomes, probabilities))\n\n    def P(self, event: set) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Probability of an event (subset of Omega).\"\"\"\n        return sum(self.p_map.get(w, 0) for w in event)\n\n    def verify_axioms(self):\n        print(\"=== Verifying Kolmogorov Axioms ===\")\n        omega_set = set(self.omega)\n        print(f\"Omega = {omega_set}\")\n        print(f\"P(Omega) = {self.P(omega_set):.4f}  (should be 1.0)\")\n        print(f\"P(empty) = {self.P(set()):.4f}      (should be 0.0)\")\n        # Countable additivity: P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B) for disjoint A, B\n        A = {self.omega[0]}\n        B = {self.omega[1]} if len(self.omega) > 1 else set()\n        print(f\"P(A∪B) = {self.P(A | B):.4f}, P(A)+P(B) = {self.P(A)+self.P(B):.4f}  (disjoint additivity)\")\n\n\n# Coin flip\ncoin = DiscreteProbabilitySpace(['H', 'T'], [0.5, 0.5])\ncoin.verify_axioms()\n","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:29:39.046788Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:29:39.047638Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:29:39.063743Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:29:39.047598Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:29:39.062746Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 2. LLM Token Distribution as a Probability Space\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef softmax(logits: np.ndarray, temperature: float = 1.0) -> np.ndarray:\n    logits = logits / temperature # scales the logits(sharpens or flatten the distribution)\n    logits -= logits.max()  # numerical stability: shifts values down, the max is 0, preventing overflow\n    exp_logits = np.exp(logits) # exponentiates each value, turning them into positive numbgers.\n    return exp_logits / exp_logits.sum() # normalises, everything sums to 1.\n\n\ndef llm_probability_space_demo():\n    \"\"\"\n    LLM next-token distribution = probability measure on vocabulary.\n    Omega = {0, 1, ..., V-1} (token IDs)\n    F = powerset (all subsets of token IDs)\n    P = softmax(logits)\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"\\n=== LLM Token Distribution as Probability Measure ===\")\n    vocab_size = 50257  # GPT-2 vocabulary size\n    np.random.seed(42)\n    logits = np.random.randn(vocab_size)\n\n    probs = softmax(logits, temperature=1.0)\n    print(f\"Vocabulary size |Omega| = {vocab_size}\")\n    print(f\"P(Omega) = sum of all probs = {probs.sum():.6f}  (= 1.0 by construction)\")\n    print(f\"All probs >= 0: {(probs >= 0).all()}\")\n\n    # Events in F are subsets of token IDs\n    # E.g., \"next token is a space character\" — in GPT-2 tokenizer, these are specific token IDs\n    # Here we simulate: \"next token is in top-k\"\n    top_k_indices = np.argsort(probs)[-100:]  # top-100 tokens\n    event_top100 = set(top_k_indices)\n    p_top100 = probs[list(event_top100)].sum()\n    print(f\"P(next token in top-100) = {p_top100:.4f}\")\n\n    # Verify σ-additivity (union of disjoint sets)\n    A = set(top_k_indices[:50])   # top 51-100\n    B = set(top_k_indices[50:])   # top 1-50\n    print(f\"P(A) + P(B) = {probs[list(A)].sum():.4f} + {probs[list(B)].sum():.4f}\")\n    print(f\"P(A ∪ B)   = {probs[list(A | B)].sum():.4f}  (must be equal since A∩B=∅)\")\n\n    # Temperature effect: how temperature changes the measure\n    print(\"\\n--- Temperature Effect on Probability Concentration ---\")\n    for temp in [0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0]:\n        p_temp = softmax(logits, temperature=temp)\n        entropy = -np.sum(p_temp * np.log(p_temp + 1e-12))\n        top1_prob = p_temp.max()\n        print(f\"  T={temp:.1f}: H(P)={entropy:.2f} bits, P(argmax)={top1_prob:.4f}\")\n\n\nllm_probability_space_demo()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:30:34.486671Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:30:34.487039Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:30:34.562345Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:30:34.487007Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:30:34.561504Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 3. Union Bound (Boole's Inequality) — Used Everywhere in ML Theory\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef union_bound_demo():\n    \"\"\"\n    P(A₁ ∪ A₂ ∪ ... ∪ Aₙ) ≤ Σᵢ P(Aᵢ)\n    This is the generalization error bound building block.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"\\n=== Union Bound — PAC Learning Connection ===\")\n    # Suppose we have n hypotheses, each with error probability δ/n\n    # By union bound: P(any hypothesis fails) ≤ n × (δ/n) = δ\n    delta = 0.05\n    for n_hypotheses in [10, 100, 1000, 10000]:\n        per_hyp_bound = delta / n_hypotheses\n        union_bound = n_hypotheses * per_hyp_bound\n        print(f\"  n={n_hypotheses:5d} hypotheses: per-hyp δ/n={per_hyp_bound:.6f}, union bound={union_bound:.4f} ≤ {delta}\")\n\n    print(\"\\nThis is exactly how LLM training theory bounds failure probability across\")\n    print(\"n model checkpoints, n random seeds, or n benchmark tasks.\")\n\n\nunion_bound_demo()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:33:16.016188Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:33:16.016712Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:33:16.023545Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:33:16.016679Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:33:16.022501Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 4. Continuity of Measure — Monotone Sequences\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef continuity_of_measure_demo():\n    \"\"\"\n    If Aₙ ↑ A (increasing), then P(Aₙ) → P(A).\n    Connection: training set grows → generalization bound tightens.\n    \"\"\"\n    print(\"\\n=== Continuity of Measure ===\")\n    # Events: A_n = {normal sample with |X| ≤ n}, X ~ N(0,1)\n    from scipy.stats import norm\n    print(\"A_n = {X ~ N(0,1) : |X| ≤ n}  →  Omega as n → ∞\")\n    for n in [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 10]:\n        p_n = norm.cdf(n) - norm.cdf(-n)\n        print(f\"  P(|X| ≤ {n:2d}) = {p_n:.6f}\")\n    print(\"  P(Omega) = 1.000000  (limit)\")\n\n\ncontinuity_of_measure_demo()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:33:48.205357Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:33:48.205679Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:33:49.603646Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:33:48.205652Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:33:49.60281Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n# 5. Visualization: LLM Probability Mass Concentration\n# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\ndef plot_probability_concentration():\n    np.random.seed(42)\n    vocab_size = 10000\n    logits = np.random.randn(vocab_size)\n    temperatures = [0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0]\n\n    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))\n\n    # Left: probability mass on top-k tokens for different temperatures\n    ax = axes[0]\n    ks = list(range(1, 201))\n    for temp in temperatures:\n        probs = softmax(logits, temp)\n        sorted_probs = np.sort(probs)[::-1]\n        cumulative = np.cumsum(sorted_probs[:200])\n        ax.plot(ks, cumulative, label=f'T={temp}')\n    ax.axhline(0.9, color='gray', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5, label='90% mass')\n    ax.set_xlabel('Top-k tokens')\n    ax.set_ylabel('Cumulative probability P(top-k)')\n    ax.set_title('LLM: Probability Mass Concentration\\n(P as measure on token space)')\n    ax.legend()\n    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n\n    # Right: sorted probability distribution (log scale)\n    ax = axes[1]\n    for temp in temperatures:\n        probs = softmax(logits, temp)\n        sorted_probs = np.sort(probs)[::-1]\n        ax.semilogy(range(1, 501), sorted_probs[:500], label=f'T={temp}')\n    ax.set_xlabel('Token rank')\n    ax.set_ylabel('Probability (log scale)')\n    ax.set_title('Sorted Token Probabilities\\n(Probability measure on vocabulary)')\n    ax.legend()\n    ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.savefig('probability_space_demo.png', dpi=150)\n    plt.show()\n    plt.close()\n    print(\"\\n[Plot saved: probability_space_demo.png]\")\n\n\nplot_probability_concentration()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:35:53.945525Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:35:53.946452Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:35:54.820457Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:35:53.946409Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:35:54.819519Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(\"\\n\" + \"=\"*60)\nprint(\"KEY TAKEAWAYS\")\nprint(\"=\"*60)\nprint(\"\"\"\n1. (Omega, F, P) is the foundation of ALL probability theory.\n2. Sigma-fields formalize 'which questions we can ask'.\n3. Probability measure = function satisfying 3 Kolmogorov axioms.\n4. LLM softmax output IS a probability measure on the vocabulary.\n5. Union bound is the workhorse of ML generalization theory.\n6. Temperature controls concentration of the measure.\n\"\"\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-06-29T03:36:16.865204Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-06-29T03:36:16.865543Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-06-29T03:36:16.871518Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-06-29T03:36:16.865513Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-06-29T03:36:16.870774Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null}]}